# interview-prep cheat sheet
Here’s a concise interview-prep cheat sheet with short answers that are easy to remember.

Topic	Short Interview Answer
# List vs Tuple	
List is mutable (can change). Tuple is immutable (cannot change), faster, and hashable if its contents are hashable.

# List vs Generator	
List stores all items in memory. Generator produces items lazily, one at a time, using less memory.

# Generator vs Iterator	
A Generator is a special type of iterator created with yield. An Iterator is any object that implements __iter__() and __next__().

# is vs ==	is 
compares object identity (same object). == compares object values (same content).

# copy vs deepcopy	copy() 
makes a shallow copy (nested objects shared). deepcopy() recursively copies all nested objects.

# Mutable vs Immutable	Mutable 
objects can be modified (list, dict, set). Immutable objects cannot (str, tuple, int, float, bool).

# @staticmethod vs @classmethod	
@staticmethod doesn’t receive self or cls. @classmethod receives cls and works with the class itself.

# *args vs **kwargs	
*args collects positional arguments into a tuple. **kwargs collects keyword arguments into a dictionary.

# Threading vs Multiprocessing	Threading 
is best for I/O-bound tasks. Multiprocessing is best for CPU-bound tasks because each process has its own Python interpreter and avoids the GIL.

# map() vs filter()	
map() transforms every item. filter() keeps only items that satisfy a condition.

# append() vs extend()
append() adds one object. extend() adds each element from another iterable.

# sorted() vs sort()	
sorted() returns a new sorted list. list.sort() sorts the original list in place.

# remove() vs pop()	
remove(value) removes by value. pop(index) removes by index and returns the removed item.

# yield vs return	
return exits the function with one value. yield pauses execution and returns values one at a time.

# global vs nonlocal	
global modifies a module-level variable. nonlocal modifies a variable in the nearest enclosing function.

# Shallow Copy vs Deep Copy	
Shallow copy copies only the outer object; nested objects are shared. Deep copy copies the entire object hierarchy independently.

Common Senior Interview One-Liners

* Why use a tuple? → “When data shouldn’t change and I want better performance or a hashable key.”
* Why use a generator? → “To process large datasets without loading everything into memory.”
* When use multiprocessing? → “For CPU-intensive work like image processing or data analysis.”
* When use threading? → “For I/O operations like API calls, databases, or file downloads.”
* When use deepcopy()? → “When nested objects must be completely independent.”
* Difference between is and ==? → “is checks identity; == checks equality.”
* When use @classmethod? → “For alternative constructors or methods that operate on the class.”
* Why yield instead of return? → “To create lazy sequences that save memory.”

These are the kinds of concise responses interviewers often expect before asking you to elaborate or write code.

